# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# DEPRECATED — Stripe keys now live in appsettings.<Env>.json.
# This file is kept only to document the env-var override convention.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Source of truth per environment:
#   Local dev   →  appsettings.Development.json   (committed test keys)
#   QA          →  appsettings.QA.json            (committed test keys)
#   UAT         →  appsettings.UAT.json           (committed test keys)
#   Production  →  Azure App Service > Configuration > Application settings
#                  (live keys MUST NOT be committed — Stripe auto-revokes leaks)
#
# How env-var overrides work in ASP.NET Core
# ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Any setting from appsettings.<Env>.json can be overridden by an env var
# named with the same path, joined with double underscores. Example:
#
#   Stripe:SecretKey  ← appsettings  →  Stripe__SecretKey  ← env var
#
# Last-loaded wins, and env vars load AFTER appsettings, so Azure App
# Service env vars always take precedence in deployed environments.
#
# Useful local override patterns
# ──────────────────────────────
#   - dotnet user-secrets set "Stripe__SecretKey" "sk_test_<your-key>"
#     (only loaded in Development; great for personal Stripe sandbox)
#
#   - $env:Stripe__WebhookSecret = "whsec_..." ; dotnet run
#     (one-off override in PowerShell, doesn't touch any file)
